output:
 By expanding the expression, we get
\begin{align*}
9z_1 z_2 + 4z_1 z_3 + z_2 z_3 &= 9z_1 z_2 + 4z_1 z_3 + z_2 z_3 \\
&= (3z_1)(3z_2) + (2z_1)(2z_3) + z_2 z_3 \\
&= (3z_1)(3z_2 + 2z_3) + z_2 z_3 \\
&= (3z_1)(z_2 + 2z_3) + z_2 z_3.
\end{align*}Thus, $|9z_1 z_2 + 4z_1 z_3 + z_2 z_3| = |3z_1||z_2 + 2z_3| + |z_2 z_3| = 9|z_2 + 2z_3| + |z_2||z_3|.$

Let $\theta_1,$ $\theta_2,$ $\theta_3$ be the arguments of $z_1,$ $z_2,$ $z_3,$ respectively. Then |z_2 + 2z_3| = |2(cos \theta_2 + 2cos \theta_3)| = 2|cos \theta_2 + 2cos \theta_3|.$ Also, we have
\[|z_1 + z_2 + z_3| = |z_2(cos \theta_2 + 2cos \theta_3) + 9(cos \theta_1 + 2cos \theta_3)|.\]Therefore,
\begin{align*}
|9z_1 z_2 + 4z_1 z_3 + z_2 z_3| &= 9|z_2||cos \theta_2 + 2cos \theta_3| + |z_2||z_3| \\
&= 9|z_2||cos \theta_2 + 2cos \theta_3| + 2|z_2||cos \theta_3| \\
&= 11|z_2||cos \theta_2 + 3cos \theta_3|.
\end{align*}Thus, $12 = 11|z_2||cos \theta_2 + 3cos \theta_3|$ and $|z_2||cos \theta_2 + 3cos \theta_3| = \frac{12}{11}.$  In particular, at least one of $|z_2|$ and $|cos \theta_2|$ must be 1, so $\theta_2 = 0$ (since $|z_1| = 1$).

