 First, we simplify the given congruences:
\begin{align*}
171 &\equiv 80 \pmod{n} \\
468 &\equiv 13 \pmod{n}
\end{align*}
We can rewrite the congruences as:
\begin{align*}
171 - 80 &= 91 \\
468 - 13 &= 455
\end{align*}
So we have $91 \equiv 0 \pmod{n}$ and $455 \equiv 0 \pmod{n}$.

To find the possible values of $n$, we need to factorize 91 and 455. We have $91 = 7 \cdot 13$ and $455 = 5 \cdot 7 \cdot 13$.

The least common multiple (LCM) of 91 and 455 is the product of the highest powers of the common prime factors, which is $5 \cdot 7 \cdot 13 = 455$. Therefore, the possible values of $n$ are the factors of 455, which are $\boxed{1, 5, 7, 13, 35, 65, 91, 455}$.

The answer is: 8

