 A function $f(x)$ is even if $f(-x) = f(x)$ for all $x$ in the domain of $f$.
A function $f(x)$ is odd if $f(-x) = -f(x)$ for all $x$ in the domain of $f$.
For $f(x) = 7x^7 - 4x^4 + 1$, we have
\begin{align*}
f(-x) &= 7(-x)^7 - 4(-x)^4 + 1 \\
&= -7x^7 - 4x^4 + 1 \\
&= -(7x^7 - 4x^4 + 1) \\
&= -f(x).
\end{align*}
Since $f(-x) = -f(x)$ for all $x$ in the domain of $f$, $f(x)$ is an $\boxed{\text{odd}}$ function.The answer is: \text{odd}

