 We can use the double angle identity for cosine, $\cos 2\theta = 2\cos^2 \theta - 1$, to write
\begin{align*}
\cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{4 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{8 \pi}{7} &= \cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cos \left(2 \cdot \frac{4 \pi}{7}\right) \cos \left(2 \cdot \frac{8 \pi}{7}\right) \\
&= \cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cdot 2\cos^2 \frac{4 \pi}{7} - \cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cdot 1 \cdot \cos \frac{8 \pi}{7} \\
&= 2 \cos^3 \frac{2 \pi}{7} - \cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cos \frac{8 \pi}{7} \\
&= 2 \cos^3 \frac{2 \pi}{7} - \cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cdot 2\cos^2 \frac{4 \pi}{7} - \cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \cdot (-1) \\
&= 2 \cos^3 \frac{2 \pi}{7} - 2\cos^3 \frac{2 \pi}{7} + \cos \frac{2 \pi}{7} \\
&= \boxed{-\frac{1}{4}}.
