Let $\begin{pmatrix}a & 0 & b \\ 0 & c & 0 \\ 0 & d & 0\end{pmatrix}$ be the normal vector of the plane.  Then $\begin{pmatrix}a & 0 & b \\ 0 & c & 0 \\ 0 & d & 0\end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix}0 \\ 2 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}2c \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix}a & 0 & b \\ 0 & c & 0 \\ 0 & d & 0\end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix}5 \\ 0 \\ 7\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}5a + 7b \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix}.$  The third equation tells us $a + b = -4 = -3 - (a + b),$ so $a + b = -4.$  Hence, there are infinitely many planes that pass through these points.  Choose $\begin{pmatrix}a & 0 & b \\ 0 & c & 0 \\ 0 & d & 0\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}4 & 0 & -4 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0\end{pmatrix}.$

Also, $\begin{pmatrix}a & 0 & b \\ 0 & c & 0 \\ 0 & d & 0\end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix}-5 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}4 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix}.$  Hence,
\[\begin{pmatrix}4 & 0 & -4 \\ 0 & 1 & 0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0\end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix}0 \\ 2 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix}1 \\ 0 \\ 2\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}4 \\ 0 \\ 0\end{pmatrix} \cdot \begin{pmatrix}1 \\ 0 \\ 2\end{pmatrix} = 4.\]Thus, the distance from the origin to the plane is $\boxed{4}.$
The answer is: 4

