output:
 \[
\begin{aligned} \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^3 &= \frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{3}{4}\cdot\frac{3}{4}\cdot\frac{3}{4}\right) \\ &= \frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{3\cdot 3 \cdot 3}{4\cdot 4 \cdot 4} \\ &= \frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{27}{64} \\ &= \frac{1}{2}\cdot\frac{27}{64} \\ &= \frac{27}{2\cdot 64} \\ &= \frac{27}{128}. \end{aligned}
\]

So, $\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{3}{4}\right)^3 = \boxed{\frac{27}{128}}$. The answer is: \frac{27}{128}

