Due to the symmetry of the curve, the line segment between $(-1,1)$ and $(1,1)$ has length $2.$  As $0 < \pi/4 < \pi/2,$ $\cos^2 t$ is concave down for $0 \le t \le \pi/4.$  Hence, the line segment between $(1, \cos^2 (\pi/4))$ and $(1 + 2\cos(2\cdot \pi/4), \cos^2 (\pi/4))$ is longer than the line segment between $(1,1)$ and $(1 + 2\cos(2\cdot \pi/4), \cos^2 (\pi/4)).$

By the Law of Cosines,
\[\cos (2 \cdot \pi/4) = \frac{(2 \cos (\pi/4))^2 - 2 \cdot (1 - \cos^2 \cdot (\pi/4)) \cos (\pi/2)}{2 \cdot 1 \cdot 2 \cos (\pi/4)}\]
Using Quadratic Formula, we can solve for $\cos \pi/4.$  Let
\[a = \cos^2 \pi/4, b = -1, c = 2 \cos^2 \pi/4 - 2 \cos \pi/2 = 2 \cos^2 \pi/4,\]so
\[a^2 + (-b)^2 - c = \cos^4 \pi/4 - 2 \cos^2 \pi/4 + 2 \cos^2 \pi/4 = \cos^4 \pi/4 = 0.\]Hence, $\cos^2 \pi/4 = \frac{1}{2}.$  Then $\cos \pi/4 = \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2},$ so the length of the line segment is
\begin{align*}
&\sqrt{4\left(1 - \left(1 - \sin^2 \frac{\pi}{2}\right) \sin \frac{\pi}{4}\right) + \left(1 - \left(1 - \cos^2 \frac{\pi}{2}\right) \cos \frac{\pi}{4}\right) \left(1 - \left(1 - \sin^2 \frac{\pi}{2}\right) \sin \frac{\pi}{4}\right) + \left(2 \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2} \cdot \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}\right)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{(\sqrt{2} - \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2})^2} \\
&= \sqrt{2 - \sqrt{2}}.
\end{align*}

